Question 5
In which lifecycle hook would you use loadScript in LWC and why?
Companies that asked this: Salesforce, TCS, IBM, Accenture, Infosys

Answer:
loadScript should be used in renderedCallback() because it needs DOM elements to be available for third-party library initialization. However, you should use proper patterns to avoid loading the script multiple times.

Why renderedCallback():

DOM elements are ready - Libraries can attach to elements

Template is fully rendered - All containers and targets exist

Can access elements - Use this.template.querySelector() safely

Library initialization possible - Can immediately initialize after loading

Why NOT other hooks:

constructor(): No DOM access, too early

connectedCallback(): DOM not rendered yet, elements not available

Example

import { LightningElement } from 'lwc';
import { loadScript } from 'lightning/platformResourceLoader';
import chartJs from '@salesforce/resourceUrl/ChartJS';
 
export default class ChartComponent extends LightningElement {
    isChartJsInitialized = false;
 
    renderedCallback() {
        if (this.isChartJsInitialized) return;
 
        this.isChartJsInitialized = true;
 
        loadScript(this, chartJs)
            .then(() => {
                const ctx = this.template.querySelector('canvas').getContext('2d');
                new Chart(ctx, {
                    type: 'bar',
                    data: { labels: ['A', 'B'], datasets: [{ data: [10, 20] }] },
                });
            })
            .catch(error => {
                console.error('Failed to load script', error);
            });
    }
}
